I have trouble simulating the blocking call in the unit tests (`NettyBlockHoundIntegrationTest`).

In my WebFlux application test suite the blocking call appears when `SingleThreadEventExecutor` is shut down and [sets `terminationFuture`](https://github.com/netty/netty/blob/363c4ecc7f2f2ec0d499ceae17c23ada5d0b0765/common/src/main/java/io/netty/util/concurrent/SingleThreadEventExecutor.java#L1051). We end up in `GlobalEventExecutor#addTask`, where we make a blocking call on the queue lock. In the tests I tried to set up  `GlobalEventExecutor#addTask` passes without blocking â€“ `tryAcquire` on the queue lock comes `true` and I don't end up in the blocking calls of `acquireQueued`.

Do you have tips on how to trigger this problem in tests? Here's what I've tried to do:
```
    @Test(timeout = 5000L)
    public void testGlobalEventExecutorAddTask() throws InterruptedException {
        CountDownLatch latch = new CountDownLatch(2);

        SingleThreadEventExecutor executor =
                new SingleThreadEventExecutor(null, new DefaultThreadFactory("test"), true) {
                    @Override
                    protected void run() {
                        while (!confirmShutdown()) {
                            Runnable task = takeTask();
                            if (task != null) {
                                task.run();
                            }
                        }
                    }
                };

        executor.execute(() -> {
            latch.countDown();
        });

        executor.terminationFuture().addListener((FutureListener) future -> latch.countDown());
        executor.shutdownGracefully();

        latch.await();
    }
```
